{\pard\sl-190\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl263\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\ql\fi480 {\f1\fs20 A most interesting sidelight appears in an article by Ritter and Kalish found in the Journal of the American Chemical Society, Volume 77, pages 4048 to 4050. This sidelight was a bit of research done by a grad student as part of his master's thesis. The grad student just happened to work out the experimental details for converting allylbenzene directly into amphetamine.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-97\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl269\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\ql\fi480 {\f1\fs20 The main thrust of the article was the good Dr. Ritter telling of his new method for converting double bonds into amines. The method which he pioneered has since come to be known as the Ritter reaction. This versatile reaction can well serve the underground operator as an alternative pathway to the amphetamines.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-90\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl279\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\ql\fi480 {\f1\fs20 The Ritter reaction in general is a reaction whereby amides are made by adding an alkene to a mixture of a nitrile in sulfuric acid. After the amide is made, it is then boiled in hydrochloric acid solution to give the corresponding amine.}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-79\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl279\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\ql\fi480 {\f1\fs20 The particular variation on this theme in which we are interested deals with the case in which the alkene is the now familiar and highly useful allylbenzene. When it is added to a solution of acetonitrile in sulfuric acid, the following reaction takes place:}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-79\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\ql{\f1\fs20 [SNiP]}\par}
}
{\pard\sl-227\slmult0\par

{\pard\plain \li0\sl279\slmult1 \ri0\nooverflow\qj\fi480 {\f1\fs20 The acetyl amide thusly produced is not isolated and purified. Rather, it is added in the crude state to hydrochloric acid, and boiled for several hours. A hydrolysis reaction almost identical to the one seen in Chapter 5 takes place producing the prototype amphetamine, benzedrine.}\par}
}\sect\sbkpage\sectd\pard\plain
